<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n08038f"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n08" href="#n08038f">N08 (VI.B.6)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n08all.htm#n08038f"> 38(f)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> communion service &amp; mass / prayers to dead / veneration of BVM / to keep consecrated / elements in church</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources"><b>The Anglican Crisis / Bishop Knox and Prayer-Book Revision</b> Rt. Rev. E. A. Knox, late Bishop of Manchester, and father of the Rev. Ronald A. Knox, who was received into the Catholic Church in 1917, in the course of a letter to &ldquo;The Times&rdquo; on the momentous crisis in the Anglican Church in connection with the Prayer-book Revision, says:&mdash; &ldquo;The Bishops have given general approval to alterations of the Prayer-book, which tend at point after point to assimilate our <mark>Communion Service to the Mass</mark>, to revive public <mark>prayers for the dead</mark>, to make Requiem Masses lawful, to increase <mark>veneration for the Virgin Mary</mark> and the Saints, and <mark>to keep, continually, a portion of the consecrated elements in the church</mark>, with the certainty that they must become elements of worship. <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font>&rdquo; <small> <a name="II13feb23" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#II13feb23"><cite title="source">Irish Independent</cite></a> (13 February 1923) 5/1</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
